sbol:Collection.ns1:description: Site directed RNA editing is an engineered tool for the posttranscriptional manipulation of RNA and proteins. Here, we demonstrate the inclusion of additional N- and C-terminal protein domains in an RNA editing-dependent manner to switch between protein isoforms in mammalian cell culture. By inclusion of localization signals, a switch of the subcellular protein localization was achieved. This included the shift from the cytoplasm to the outer-membrane, which typically is inaccessible at the protein-level. Furthermore, the strategy allows to implement photocaging to achieve spatiotemporal control of isoform switching. The strategy does not require substantial genetic engineering, and might well complement current optogenetic and optochemical approaches.
